**New Zealand** competed at the **[2018 Commonwealth
Games](/wiki/2018_Commonwealth_Games "2018 Commonwealth Games")** in [Gold
Coast](/wiki/Gold_Coast,_Queensland "Gold Coast, Queensland"), Australia, from
4 to 15 April 2018.[3] It was the nations’s 21st appearance at the
Commonwealth Games, having competed at every Games since their inception in
1930. The New Zealand team consisted of 251 athletes, 130 men and 121 women,
across 17 sports.

The New Zealand team collected 46 medals: 15 gold, 16 silver and 15 bronze, an
increase of one medal from the [previous games](/wiki/2014_Commonwealth_Games
"2014 Commonwealth Games"). The medals came across twelve sports. The nation
won its first medal in beach volleyball, which was introduced at the Games,
and its first gold medal in hockey.

Commonwealth Games")

The NZOC announced fifteen athletes to compete at the games on 2 February
2018.[7] Para-athlete Holly Robinson had been confirmed on 22 November
2017.[8] Brothers Jake and Zane Robertson were added on 9 February 2018.[9]
Sprinter Joseph Millar was added on 23 February 2018.[10] Siositina Hakeai was
conditionally added on 28 February 2018.[11] Zane Robertson withdrew from the
team on 5 April 2018.[12]

race, leaving Bond to focus solely on the time trial, on 22 March 2018.[22]

Games](/wiki/Hockey_at_the_2018_Commonwealth_Games "Hockey at the 2018
Commonwealth Games")

New Zealand has qualified both men's and women's hockey teams for a total of
36 athletes (18 men and 18 women). Both teams qualified as being one of the
top nine teams in the Commonwealth (besides the host nation, Australia)
according to their [FIH World Rankings](/wiki/FIH_World_Rankings "FIH World
Rankings") as of 31 October 2017.

##
Netball[[edit](/w/index.php?title=New_Zealand_at_the_2018_Commonwealth_Games&action=edit&section=24
"Edit section: Netball")]

Main article: [Netball at the 2018 Commonwealth
Games](/wiki/Netball_at_the_2018_Commonwealth_Games "Netball at the 2018
Commonwealth Games")

New Zealand qualified a netball team by virtue of being ranked in the top 11
(excluding the host nation, Australia) of the [INF World
Rankings](/wiki/INF_World_Rankings "INF World Rankings") on 1 July
2017.[28][29][30] The team was announced on 8 February 2018.[31]

Roster

## Rugby

"Edit section: Rugby sevens")]

Main article: [Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth
Games](/wiki/Rugby_sevens_at_the_2018_Commonwealth_Games "Rugby sevens at the
2018 Commonwealth Games")

The [New Zealand men's side](/wiki/New_Zealand_national_rugby_sevens_team "New
Zealand national rugby sevens team") qualified due to their [2016–17 World
Rugby Sevens Series](/wiki/2016%E2%80%9317_World_Rugby_Sevens_Series "2016–17
World Rugby Sevens Series") ranking, while the [New Zealand women's
side](/wiki/New_Zealand_women%27s_national_rugby_sevens_team "New Zealand
women's national rugby sevens team") qualified due to their [2016–17 World
Rugby Women's Sevens
Series](/wiki/2016%E2%80%9317_World_Rugby_Women%27s_Sevens_Series "2016–17
World Rugby Women's Sevens Series") ranking. Both the men's and women's teams
were announced on 21 March 2018.[32]
